      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Energy Plan: Points of Light, and Heat</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Bernard C Melewski (Adirondack Council) replies to May 18 editorial, saying there is one good idea in Pres Bush's energy plan, its support for legislation to control acid rain; cartoon</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Misguided Energy Proposal'' (editorial, May 18): There is one good idea in the president's energy plan that has received little attention: new acid rain legislation.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Misguided Energy Proposal'' (editorial, May 18): There is one good idea in the president's energy plan that has received little attention: new acid rain legislation.</p>
        <p>The plan recommends that the Environmental Protection Agency administrator propose legislation not unlike the acid rain control bill, which would require mandatory cuts in sulfur dioxide, nitrogen oxide and mercury -- the three air pollutants associated with acid rain. The plan's proposal to end acid rain's destruction should not be lost on the leadership of both political parties.</p>
        <p>BERNARD C. MELEWSKI  Legislative Dir., Adirondack Council  Albany, May 18, 2001</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
